Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: The Court WILL consider expungement if Defendant successfully completes all conditions of probation with no new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding.

Statements made as to Sentencing by both counsel and the Defendant.

THE COURT ORDERED THE Defendant to serve 120 DAYS in the House of Correction (HOC) with credit for 3 days time served.  Huber privileges under Sec.303.08 Wis. Stats. to apply for work and school.

Court IMPOSED AND STAYED the sentence and placed Defendant on Probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 1 YEAR with the following conditions:
*  No new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding.
*  Cooperate with agent.
*  Court waived all court costs. Defendant is indigent
*  Maintain full time / part time employment and or schooling.
*  Maintain ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
*  AODA assessment with follow up care and treatment.
*  Random urine screens with no positive results. No association with drug users, drug dealers, drug houses, or drug dealings.
*  Community service 20 hours.
*  Restitution set at $1,010.00 to JC Penney to be paid out of bail on deposit, if any; and the balance due prior to the end of the probationary period.  Failure to pay shall result in a Civil Judgment.
*  No contact with JC Penney located at 5350 S. 76th Street, in the Village of Greendale, County of Milwaukee. 
*  Court ordered the Defendant to write a letter of apology to JC Penney.

The Court WILL consider expungement if Defendant successfully completes all conditions of probation with no new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding. 

Received and filed with the court:
*  Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief Form
*  Pretrial Incarceration Credit Form

Court found the Defendant guilty as charged in the complaint.  Judgment of Conviction entered. Parties are prepared to proceed with Sentencing.
